<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1257]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,403,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet comes from the 
<typeStatus box="[751,799,404,430]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">type</typeStatus>
locality, near the Tequendama waterfall, one of the most important sacred places in the Muisca civilization, a Chibcha-speaking indigenous people who inhabit the central highlands of the eastern Andes in 
<collectingCountry box="[530,644,475,501]" name="Colombia" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. To be treated as an arbitrary combination of letters, and hence without the need to agree in gender with the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1257]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,547,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName authority="Muñoz-Charry &amp; Galvis &amp; Martínez, 2022" authorityName="Muñoz-Charry &amp; Galvis &amp; Martínez" authorityYear="2022" box="[443,613,547,573]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lapsias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tequendama" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[443,613,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">L. tequendama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[623,716,547,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[623,716,547,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be recognized from those of the remaining species in the genus by their longer and stronger embolus (e), with several bumps/apophyses on it, a long median apophysis (ma), a prolateral long and pointed accessory tegular apophysis (pTa) and the retrolateral tibial apophysis (RTA) curved and projected outward (
<figureCitation box="[416,547,655,682]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[151,1412,892,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-403@6.[151,1436,885,1885]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. L. tequedama sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 8268), 20 habitus; 21, 24 left palp, ventral view; 22, 25 same, retrolateral view; 23 same, dorsal view; 26 same, prolateral view. Abbreviations: e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, pTa=prolateral tegular apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (20), 0.5 mm (21– 26)." pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Figs 21–26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1257]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,551,691,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
Description. Male (
<typeStatus box="[430,538,691,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">holotype</typeStatus>
).
</emphasis>
Total length: 5.40. Carapace brown with a medial yellow arrow-shaped mark and two yellow posterolateral lines, 2.52 long, 1.95 wide, 1.58 high (
<figureCitation box="[956,1044,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[151,1412,892,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-403@6.[151,1436,885,1885]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. L. tequedama sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 8268), 20 habitus; 21, 24 left palp, ventral view; 22, 25 same, retrolateral view; 23 same, dorsal view; 26 same, prolateral view. Abbreviations: e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, pTa=prolateral tegular apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (20), 0.5 mm (21– 26)." pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
). OC brown-reddish with eyes on black marks, 1.13 long. Anterior eye row 1.73 wide and posterior 1.73 wide. Sternum yellowish, 1.08 long, 0.94 wide. Labium yellowish, 0.48 long, 0.41 wide. Chelicerae brown, with two retromarginal and three promarginal teeth. Palp brown-yellowish, with thick embolus (e) that emerge wide in base and has several irregularities along accompanying by a knife-like accessory tegular apophysis (pTa), hook-like median apophysis (ma) surrounded by membranous tissue, the retrolateral tibial apophysis (RTA) curved and projected ventral (
<figureCitation box="[1141,1271,907,934]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[151,1412,892,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-403@6.[151,1436,885,1885]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. L. tequedama sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 8268), 20 habitus; 21, 24 left palp, ventral view; 22, 25 same, retrolateral view; 23 same, dorsal view; 26 same, prolateral view. Abbreviations: e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, pTa=prolateral tegular apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (20), 0.5 mm (21– 26)." pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Figs 21–26</figureCitation>
). Leg formula: 4132, all yellow with black marks. Leg macrosetae: femur, I p 1 di, d 1 di; II–IV p 1 di, d 2 di; patella, I–II p 1 me; III– IV p 1 me, r 1 me; tibia, I v 2–2–2, p 1–0–1; II v 1–2–2, p 1–0–1; III v 2–0–2, p 1–0–1, r 1–0–1; IV v 1–0–2, p 1–0–1, r 1–0–1; metatarsus, I v 2–2, p 1–1; II v 2–2, p 1–1, r 1 –1; III–IV v 1–1–1, p 1–1–2, r 1–1–2. Abdomen light yellow with an anteromedial dark brown spot and posteromedial chevron marks (
<figureCitation box="[1061,1145,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[151,1412,892,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-403@6.[151,1436,885,1885]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. L. tequedama sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 8268), 20 habitus; 21, 24 left palp, ventral view; 22, 25 same, retrolateral view; 23 same, dorsal view; 26 same, prolateral view. Abbreviations: e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, pTa=prolateral tegular apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (20), 0.5 mm (21– 26)." pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1257]" box="[199,1042,1087,1114]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1087,1113]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Variation.</emphasis>
(n= 
<specimenCount box="[365,453,1087,1114]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="male">2 males</specimenCount>
) Total length 5.36–5.40. Carapace length 2.52–2.53.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1257]" box="[199,418,1123,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1123,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1257]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,542,1159,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Distribution and Comments.</emphasis>
Known only from its 
<typeStatus box="[794,842,1160,1186]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">type</typeStatus>
locality in the Colombian Andes (
<figureCitation box="[1232,1317,1159,1186]" captionStart="FIGURE 57" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1890,1914]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-22@15.[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 57. Distribution of jumping spiders of the tribe Lapsiini Maddison (Salticidae: Spartaeinae) in South America. The figures with a dot inside represent the type species of each genus." pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,1160,1186]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">type</typeStatus>
specimens were collected beating a rotten trunk and manually in the night over low vegetation in a high-Andean secondary moist forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
